{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516507"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12642"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12642"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.79,0.02,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60271"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5123"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12642"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45693"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1012"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"4069"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9051"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44382"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60271"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old man presents to a rural hospital with a two-week history of fever, night sweats, chest pain and joint pain. He has no known medical conditions and takes no regular medications. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history, drinks alcohol heavily. He has recently returned from a one week trip to Bali where he underwent a dental procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.3\u00b0C. The patient has multiple painless, erythematous macules on his palms. On auscultation, a new systolic murmur is noted at the left sternal border. Investigations reveal a haemoglobin of 78 g/L (135-175) and white cell count of 15 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Q fever","HIV seroconversion","Infective endocarditis","Malaria","Rheumatic fever"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the symptoms and examination findings, the most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Einfective endocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient presents with classic features of endocarditis, including prolonged fever, night sweats, joint pain, and a new systolic murmur. The presence of painless, erythematous macules on the palms is highly suggestive of Janeway lesions, which are characteristic of infective endocarditis. These lesions are caused by septic emboli and are non-tender, unlike the painful Osler\u0027s nodes also seen in endocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe source of his infection is likely to be the dental procedure, and other risk factors include poor dental hygiene, congenital heart defects, valvular heart disease, pacemaker or implantable cardioverter-defibrillators, and intravenous drug use. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe low haemoglobin level may indicate haemolytic anaemia, which can uncommonly occur in endocarditis due to mechanical destruction of red blood cells by the infected, roughened valve surfaces. The elevated white cell count suggests an ongoing inflammatory or infectious process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQ fever\u003C/strong\u003E is a bacterial infection caused by Coxiella burnetii, and is most often acquired from contact with livestock, mainly cattle, sheep, and goats. While it can cause fever and joint pain, it typically does not cause a heart murmur or the peripheral stigmata of endocarditis seen in this patient. Q fever endocarditis is possible but much rarer and usually occurs in patients with pre-existing valvular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHIV seroconversion\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever, fatigue, and joint pain. However, the duration of symptoms (two weeks) is longer than typical for acute HIV infection, and HIV seroconversion does not explain the new heart murmur or Janeway lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalaria\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fever, chills, and joint pain, however there is no malaria transmission in the tourist areas of Bali and malaria would not explain the new heart murmur or Janeway lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fever, joint pain, and heart murmurs due to valvulitis. However, rheumatic fever typically occurs as a delayed complication of streptococcal pharyngitis, which is not mentioned in this patient\u0027s history. Additionally, the peripheral stigmata (Janeway lesions) and risk factors (dental procedure) are more consistent with infective endocarditis than rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of prolonged fever, new heart murmur, Janeway lesions, and risk factors (dental procedure) strongly supports the diagnosis of infective endocarditis. The next steps in management would include blood cultures, echocardiography, and empiric antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Infective endocarditis (IE) is an infection of the inner lining of the heart, typically involving the heart valves.","Classic signs of infective endocarditis include fever, new or changing heart murmur, and peripheral stigmata such as Janeway lesions or Osler\u0027s nodes.","Risk factors for infective endocarditis include intravenous drug use, prosthetic heart valves, and certain congenital heart defects."],"references":["Yallowitz AW, Decker LC. Infectious Endocarditis. [Updated 2022 Apr 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-.","Beaulieu A, Rehman HU. Janeway lesions. CMAJ. 2010 Jul 13;182(10):1075. doi: 10.1503/cmaj.091528. Epub 2010 May 10. PMID: 20457771; PMCID: PMC2900332."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45693"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12642"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45693"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T18:22:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T18:22:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5123"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60271"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda